58–Afdød","1381–1451":"1381–1451","1383–1438":"1383–1438","1385–Male":"1385–Afdød","1327–Male":"1327–Afdød","1330–Female":"1330–Afdød","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1451":"1451","1351":"1351","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1327":"1327","1358":"1358","1357":"1357","1388":"1388","1353":"1353","1438":"1438","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Skotland","Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Otterburn, Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"1353–1388":"1353–1388","1357–Male":"1357–Overleden","1358–Male":"1358–Overleden","1381–1451":"1381–1451","1383–1438":"1383–1438","1385–Male":"1385–Overleden","1327–Male":"1327–Overleden","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1451":"1451","1351":"1351","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1327":"1327","1358":"1358","1357":"1357","1388":"1388","1353":"1353","1438":"1438","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Schotland","Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Otterburn, Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"1353–1388":"1353–1388","1357–Male":"1357–Deceased","1358–Male":"1358–Deceased","1381–1451":"1381–1451","1383–1438":"1383–1438","1385–Male":"1385–Deceased","1327–Male":"1327–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1451":"1451","1351":"1351","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1327":"1327","1358":"1358","1357":"1357","1388":"1388","1353":"1353","1438":"1438","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Otterburn, Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Moray in northeastern Scotland, which derives from Celtic <i>mori-</i> ‘sea’ + <i>treb-</i> ‘settlement’. The founder of the Scottish house of Murray was a Fleming named Freskin who was granted Strathbrock in West Lothian and Duffus in Moray by David I. The family took its name from the region in the late 12th century.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of   McMurray  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muireadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muireadhach</i>’ a personal name meaning ‘mariner’. Occasionally it may be a shortened form of   McMurray  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Murri","meanings":["Probably Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murry","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murrah","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Murie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel.","Scottish: habitational name from Murie in Errol (Perthshire).","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"Merhi","meanings":["Arabic (mainly Lebanon and Syria): from a variant of the personal name <i>Mirhi</i> of unknown meaning. Bearers of this surname are both Muslims and Christians. Compare   Murray   5."]},{"name":"Murrey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Murray  ."]},{"name":"McMurray","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muireadhaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muireadhaich</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Muireadhach</i> ‘seafarer’ (see   Murdoch  ). Compare   McCurry   1."]},{"name":"Murra","meanings":["Italian (Sicily): topographic name from Sicilian <i>murra</i> ‘large rock, mass of rocks’ or a habitational name from a place called with this word.","East Frisian: unexplained.","Albanian: nickname from <i>murrë</i> (definite form <i>murra</i>) ‘dark gray cow’."]},{"name":"Murrie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Murray  ."]}]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Patrick Murray was born in 1353, in Cockpool, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Adam Murray, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Adam Murray, was 23. He had at least 3 sons. He died in 1388, in Otterburn, Northumberland, England, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1353–1388":"1353–1388","1357–Male":"1357–Su